WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.580 --> 00:00:04.939
My name is Ginny Foos, and I'm honored to be here. And it actually brings back

00:00:04.939 --> 00:00:09.619
some really great memories. When I was ten,

00:00:09.619 --> 00:00:13.350
I was on a television show outside of WGBH

00:00:13.350 --> 00:00:18.650
in Boston, which is where I grew up. And I was one of five panelists that

00:00:18.650 --> 00:00:23.060
had disabilities. And we, filmed for two years.

00:00:23.060 --> 00:00:25.678
And it was a real coming of age experience

00:00:25.678 --> 00:00:28.681
for me because, we were asked to sit on very hot

00:00:28.681 --> 00:00:33.224
seats, talking about how do you feel about being different, how

00:00:33.224 --> 00:00:36.963
do you feel about being teased. And not only was I

00:00:36.963 --> 00:00:41.642
saving in psychological cost, I didn't have to see a shrink.

00:00:43.506 --> 00:00:45.545
&gt;&gt; I was actually being paid for talking about my feelings. And

00:00:45.545 --> 00:00:50.240
I really bonded with the other four individuals. And it was really neat.

00:00:50.240 --> 00:00:54.080
unfortunately, we did not stay on air for

00:00:54.080 --> 00:00:58.040
the two years, but scholastic educational services picked us

00:00:58.040 --> 00:01:00.930
up. And this was right when the mainstreaming act

00:01:00.930 --> 00:01:03.492
was really coming into play. When, when I started

00:01:03.492 --> 00:01:05.305
kindergarten, I was not allowed to go to the

00:01:05.305 --> 00:01:07.250
local school. I had to go to a special

00:01:07.250 --> 00:01:10.540
school, even though intellectually I'm no different than you

00:01:10.540 --> 00:01:15.410
are. but the mainstreaming act took place in 1972.

00:01:15.410 --> 00:01:15.990
&gt;&gt; Mm-hm.

00:01:15.990 --> 00:01:19.620
&gt;&gt; And by first grade, I was then able to go to a local public

00:01:19.620 --> 00:01:22.550
school. So, jump ahead seven or eight years,

00:01:22.550 --> 00:01:24.830
which was when we were filming Feeling Free.

00:01:25.910 --> 00:01:27.470
The, the thought was, we, we have to

00:01:27.470 --> 00:01:32.440
expose the public to diversity so that students

00:01:32.440 --> 00:01:35.380
can become comfortable when these other students are

00:01:35.380 --> 00:01:37.350
suddenly sitting in the desk next to theirs.

00:01:37.350 --> 00:01:38.140
&gt;&gt; Right!

00:01:38.140 --> 00:01:40.210
&gt;&gt; So it was a really neat experience,

00:01:41.340 --> 00:01:46.490
my other panelists, or, friends, I guess, would be the better word. we, we, we

00:01:46.490 --> 00:01:49.280
did audition, and, so, they were able

00:01:49.280 --> 00:01:51.500
to get some of really awesome articulate kids.

00:01:51.500 --> 00:01:52.263
&gt;&gt; Mm-hm

00:01:52.263 --> 00:01:55.812
&gt;&gt; One had cerebral palsy, one became blind

00:01:55.812 --> 00:01:59.260
during the process of our show. And so

00:01:59.260 --> 00:02:02.680
that was very interesting to befriend somebody that's,

00:02:02.680 --> 00:02:04.940
I, when I first met her could see.

00:02:04.940 --> 00:02:05.720
&gt;&gt; Mm-hm

00:02:05.720 --> 00:02:06.480
&gt;&gt; And when we

00:02:06.480 --> 00:02:08.199
finished, could not see at all.

00:02:08.199 --> 00:02:10.220
&gt;&gt; And remind me again, how old were you at this time?

00:02:10.220 --> 00:02:15.830
&gt;&gt; I was, ten. Ten to 12. Right in those crucial years, yeah.

00:02:15.830 --> 00:02:18.040
&gt;&gt; So at, was this the same age where you

00:02:18.040 --> 00:02:20.790
were noticing, I mean, how old were you when you,

00:02:20.790 --> 00:02:23.780
sort of, noticed yourself that you were different from other

00:02:23.780 --> 00:02:26.530
people. And maybe you, when your parents also noticed this.

00:02:26.530 --> 00:02:29.060
&gt;&gt; That's a really good question. my

00:02:29.060 --> 00:02:31.580
parents were given the diagnosis when I was

00:02:31.580 --> 00:02:35.660
18 months old. And they wonder to this day

00:02:35.660 --> 00:02:38.570
whether or not that was a delayed diagnosis that

00:02:38.570 --> 00:02:44.250
no one had the heart to break it to them. now this was pre DNA testing, this was

00:02:44.250 --> 00:02:48.200
all based on X-rays, and femur length. Femur is

00:02:48.200 --> 00:02:50.010
what they really go for in measuring the femur

00:02:50.010 --> 00:02:53.470
length. and there we were sitting in Boston, one

00:02:53.470 --> 00:02:57.310
of the top medical communities in the country and

00:02:57.310 --> 00:03:01.820
the gentleman that gave my parents the, diagnosis

00:03:01.820 --> 00:03:04.745
was T Barry Brazefin, who was sort of the

00:03:04.745 --> 00:03:08.310
Dr. Spock, not the Sci Fi doctor Spock but

00:03:08.310 --> 00:03:12.300
the sort of, the pediatric voice of America in

00:03:12.300 --> 00:03:17.520
the 70s. And so I love to tell people that I was diagnosed by that man, myself.

00:03:17.520 --> 00:03:19.380
So they knew when I was 18 months old.

00:03:19.380 --> 00:03:22.470
I think many little people like myself did not

00:03:22.470 --> 00:03:24.280
come to their own realization until they're in school.

00:03:24.280 --> 00:03:25.373
&gt;&gt; Mm-hm.

00:03:25.373 --> 00:03:27.850
&gt;&gt; Because that's when the teasing really starts.

00:03:27.850 --> 00:03:28.020
&gt;&gt; Sure.

00:03:28.020 --> 00:03:32.580
&gt;&gt; And the accessibility, if you will. Especially back then.

00:03:32.580 --> 00:03:35.960
You know we're talking about the 70's. There wasn't any

00:03:35.960 --> 00:03:38.850
Americans with Disability Act. So that's when I was having

00:03:38.850 --> 00:03:45.300
to struggle to, to access what my fellow students were accessing.

00:03:45.300 --> 00:03:47.300
&gt;&gt; Did you notice so,

00:03:47.300 --> 00:03:50.120
what kind of, experience did you have with

00:03:50.120 --> 00:03:52.480
other students? Was it entirely negative from the

00:03:52.480 --> 00:03:54.870
beginning? I mean, did, were people, you know,

00:03:54.870 --> 00:03:56.940
were kids mean, were they, did they tease a

00:03:56.940 --> 00:03:59.740
lot, did they, you know, did the just

00:03:59.740 --> 00:04:03.230
sort of look unsure, you know, seeing something different

00:04:03.230 --> 00:04:05.550
from themselves, what kind of interaction was it,

00:04:05.550 --> 00:04:07.730
and did it change as you went through schooling?

00:04:08.830 --> 00:04:13.410
&gt;&gt; luckily, I grew up in a very educated community.

00:04:13.410 --> 00:04:17.430
You know, 30 minutes away from MIT, Harvard, you know,

00:04:17.430 --> 00:04:21.310
all of the Ivy Leagues in Boston. and I think

00:04:21.310 --> 00:04:25.560
that's, that speaks a lot to,

00:04:27.150 --> 00:04:32.090
kids and their val, you don't have value system but their manners and so forth.

00:04:32.090 --> 00:04:32.240
&gt;&gt; Sure.

00:04:32.240 --> 00:04:38.410
&gt;&gt; So I don't remember getting teased too much. I'm sure I did and how

00:04:38.410 --> 00:04:41.120
much of that I have sort of put under the surface.

00:04:41.120 --> 00:04:41.175
&gt;&gt; Mm-hm.

00:04:41.175 --> 00:04:47.790
&gt;&gt; And forgotten about. but I, I don't it, I have a tougher time even today

00:04:47.790 --> 00:04:53.410
when I'm in an inner-city environment where my, the people surrounding me, don't

00:04:53.410 --> 00:04:55.170
have the same etiquette. And don't have

00:04:55.170 --> 00:04:58.120
the same education, the same exposure. And that's

00:04:58.120 --> 00:05:03.630
really where I struggle more than where I grew up. In a suburb of Boston.

00:05:03.630 --> 00:05:08.850
&gt;&gt; Well,to get a bit more of that sort of educated thought and idea I

00:05:08.850 --> 00:05:14.340
want you to tell us you know, as a medical condition of dwarfism

00:05:14.340 --> 00:05:19.310
what is, what do you know is the cause of shorter stature? And in

00:05:19.310 --> 00:05:23.000
particular in your case, what is the, what is the cause of, of this?

00:05:23.000 --> 00:05:25.870
&gt;&gt; Well, remember there are over 200 different types

00:05:25.870 --> 00:05:28.690
of dwarfism, achondroplasia being the most common. So if

00:05:28.690 --> 00:05:30.590
you were to meet another little person in your life,

00:05:30.590 --> 00:05:33.290
most likely they would have achondroplasia. So I can only

00:05:33.290 --> 00:05:36.510
really speak to achondroplasia. it is a dominant gene, it

00:05:36.510 --> 00:05:39.720
is also a mutation. So, what that means is, an

00:05:39.720 --> 00:05:43.690
individual can have achondroplasia for two reasons. One would be

00:05:43.690 --> 00:05:45.890
their parents have it, and it's been inherited as it

00:05:45.890 --> 00:05:49.330
was with my children. The other would be, it's a

00:05:49.330 --> 00:05:53.740
genetic mutation, which is a complete Unexplained event, which is

00:05:53.740 --> 00:05:58.000
what it was for me. I, I'm the only little person in my family. My little

00:05:58.000 --> 00:06:02.300
brother is six three and my parents, my

00:06:02.300 --> 00:06:04.860
grandfather was a genologist so you can image

00:06:04.860 --> 00:06:10.310
he spent a lot of time looking into this. and I am the only dwarf in my family

00:06:10.310 --> 00:06:16.008
of origin. But I then went on to meet my husband who also has achodroplasia.

00:06:16.008 --> 00:06:16.361
&gt;&gt; Okay

00:06:16.361 --> 00:06:18.890
&gt;&gt; We got married and we

00:06:18.890 --> 00:06:23.300
have three children. I gave birth to two of them and I flew to Moscow for the

00:06:23.300 --> 00:06:27.180
third one. To adopt from an orphanage. who also

00:06:27.180 --> 00:06:29.760
has achondroplasia but clearly not from me or my

00:06:29.760 --> 00:06:34.590
husband, she, from all we know, which is

00:06:34.590 --> 00:06:37.190
really not much, is a mutation as well, her

00:06:37.190 --> 00:06:40.870
parents were average height and I suspect in Russia,

00:06:41.880 --> 00:06:43.960
it's a lot harder to be a little person.

00:06:43.960 --> 00:06:44.390
&gt;&gt; Sure

00:06:44.390 --> 00:06:44.700
&gt;&gt; Yeah

00:06:44.700 --> 00:06:46.520
&gt;&gt; Are you familiar with the gene that

00:06:46.520 --> 00:06:48.990
is actually mutated in most cases of achondroplasia?

00:06:48.990 --> 00:06:52.610
&gt;&gt; The FR. The FGFR3 gene.

00:06:52.610 --> 00:06:54.000
&gt;&gt; That's it. That's what I am.

00:06:54.000 --> 00:06:54.890
&gt;&gt; okay.

00:06:54.890 --> 00:06:57.390
&gt;&gt; There's a reason I don't teach science. I'm, I'm an

00:06:57.390 --> 00:07:00.850
English and drama teacher and Spanish teacher not a science teacher. So

00:07:00.850 --> 00:07:03.400
yes, very familiar. I, I don't spend a whole lot of

00:07:03.400 --> 00:07:10.310
time conversing about it. what is really, really cool is that when

00:07:10.310 --> 00:07:19.520
the gene was discovered. In 1994. In 1992, the National Convention was in

00:07:19.520 --> 00:07:24.890
San Francisco. I was eight months pregnant. We had both my in-laws there as well

00:07:24.890 --> 00:07:29.590
as my parents, and when we have a National Convention that Little People of

00:07:29.590 --> 00:07:32.710
America puts on. A gaggle of healthcare

00:07:32.710 --> 00:07:35.490
providers fly in, that have specialized or have

00:07:35.490 --> 00:07:40.690
an interest in, dwarfism. And so, they'll be no less

00:07:40.690 --> 00:07:45.610
than 15 or 20 geneticists from around the country. Sometimes we

00:07:45.610 --> 00:07:50.500
even have international geneticists. And we all volunteered ourselves for

00:07:50.500 --> 00:07:55.430
blood draw, when I was eight months pregnant. And they sent me

00:07:55.430 --> 00:08:00.520
home with a vial for umbilical blo, blood that I was,

00:08:00.520 --> 00:08:03.040
when I was going to give birth a month later

00:08:03.040 --> 00:08:06.580
so that they could get umbilical cord blood. So, I

00:08:06.580 --> 00:08:08.750
like to say we had a little bit of something

00:08:08.750 --> 00:08:11.790
to do with the discovery of the gene two years later.

00:08:11.790 --> 00:08:12.570
&gt;&gt; Absolutely.

00:08:12.570 --> 00:08:18.550
&gt;&gt; Now, on that note I have two children that I gave birth to. One in

00:08:18.550 --> 00:08:24.854
August of 1992, the other in November of 1997. The gene was discovered in

00:08:24.854 --> 00:08:31.911
1994 or 5. So that meant that my pregnancies were very, very different. In 1992,

00:08:31.911 --> 00:08:35.278
the only diagnostic tool that they could use

00:08:35.278 --> 00:08:38.933
was ultrasound. And again, they were looking at

00:08:38.933 --> 00:08:44.067
the femur in the fetus And they could not measure that accurately until I was 24

00:08:44.067 --> 00:08:49.930
weeks pregnant. So at that time, they told me, and I was actually being seen

00:08:49.930 --> 00:08:55.990
by the gentleman that wrote the growth charts for fetuses at UCSF,

00:08:55.990 --> 00:09:01.980
and he was the one reading my film, my, my measurements, from the ultrasound.

00:09:01.980 --> 00:09:05.290
And he said, Jenny, this is a tough one. He said, that femur

00:09:05.290 --> 00:09:11.670
is in the seventh percentile. And typically, if we're looking at a heterozygote.

00:09:11.670 --> 00:09:11.980
&gt;&gt; Mm hm.

00:09:11.980 --> 00:09:15.000
&gt;&gt; Meaning that the embryo fetus has gotten the gene

00:09:15.000 --> 00:09:17.500
from one of you. That femur is going to be

00:09:17.500 --> 00:09:21.070
over the tenth percentile. Right around, between the tenth

00:09:21.070 --> 00:09:24.330
and the twentieth or thirtieth, or something. and you're

00:09:24.330 --> 00:09:27.160
coming in at the seventh, and that makes us very

00:09:27.160 --> 00:09:29.891
concerned, that perhaps you are carrying a homozygote. And

00:09:29.891 --> 00:09:34.210
a homozygote, what that means in, in lay term

00:09:34.210 --> 00:09:37.620
is a double dominant. And in achondroplasia, they have

00:09:37.620 --> 00:09:40.540
found that to be lethal. The baby is born and

00:09:40.540 --> 00:09:42.730
lives no more than a week. Typically more

00:09:42.730 --> 00:09:47.210
a matter of hours. Without life support. So

00:09:47.210 --> 00:09:54.140
it was a really tough call. So, we went ahead and, and, went with what we

00:09:54.140 --> 00:09:56.680
thought was right, and Alex was born, and

00:09:56.680 --> 00:09:58.510
obviously he's still with us. He's 20 years

00:09:58.510 --> 00:10:02.780
old, so he must be a heterozygote. Although he has had a lot of medical issues.

00:10:02.780 --> 00:10:03.160
&gt;&gt; True.

00:10:03.160 --> 00:10:05.780
&gt;&gt; jump ahead five years

00:10:05.780 --> 00:10:07.730
later, and in between that, by the way,

00:10:07.730 --> 00:10:09.570
I'd flew to Moscow to adopt the second child.

00:10:10.910 --> 00:10:14.620
I'm pregnant again with our now 15 year old,

00:10:14.620 --> 00:10:18.700
and I have an amniocentesis at ten weeks. And

00:10:18.700 --> 00:10:20.570
within a week, I get a phone call

00:10:20.570 --> 00:10:23.370
from a genetic counsellor at Baylor University in Texas

00:10:23.370 --> 00:10:27.650
telling me, you have a heterozygote. 100% certainty. So

00:10:27.650 --> 00:10:30.940
you can imagine the difference in the stress involved

00:10:30.940 --> 00:10:32.490
around both pregnancies.

00:10:32.490 --> 00:10:36.520
&gt;&gt; So do you think it's a, in your mind, knowing

00:10:36.520 --> 00:10:41.510
in advance, is a good thing. You want to know even

00:10:41.510 --> 00:10:46.620
aside from your case. Cause there's also a possibility that if

00:10:46.620 --> 00:10:51.885
you're two heterozygotes have children that neither that a child gets. But.

00:10:51.885 --> 00:10:52.820
&gt;&gt; Does not get the gene.

00:10:52.820 --> 00:10:53.910
&gt;&gt; Does not get the gene.

00:10:53.910 --> 00:10:56.140
&gt;&gt; So what that means in lay terms is I could have had you.

00:10:56.140 --> 00:10:57.540
You could have been my child!

00:10:57.540 --> 00:10:58.180
&gt;&gt; Exactly.

00:10:58.180 --> 00:11:01.930
&gt;&gt; I would have been 15, but nonetheless. So there is as much

00:11:01.930 --> 00:11:05.270
of a possibility that I would have what we would call an average sized

00:11:05.270 --> 00:11:08.350
child or even an above average sized child. I have friends that are

00:11:08.350 --> 00:11:13.370
my size, very good friends. Whose only child, a son, is six foot four.

00:11:13.370 --> 00:11:14.265
&gt;&gt; Mm-hm.

00:11:14.265 --> 00:11:17.150
&gt;&gt; So, I had as big of a chance of that as

00:11:17.150 --> 00:11:21.820
I had of a lethal situation. Both of those being 25% chance.

00:11:21.820 --> 00:11:25.140
And then I had a 50% chance of having the hetrozygote where

00:11:25.140 --> 00:11:28.110
the kid gets the gene from either me or my, or my husband.

00:11:28.110 --> 00:11:28.321
&gt;&gt; Mm-hm.

00:11:28.321 --> 00:11:29.580
&gt;&gt; And that's what we wound up with.

00:11:29.580 --> 00:11:33.400
We did never, we never experienced the, homozygote, thankfully.

00:11:33.400 --> 00:11:34.740
&gt;&gt; Thankfully, yeah.

00:11:34.740 --> 00:11:36.530
&gt;&gt; Although I have many friends that have.

00:11:36.530 --> 00:11:42.150
&gt;&gt; What, so now I'd like to, just maybe talk a bit more about that, because

00:11:42.150 --> 00:11:43.620
that seems like it could be a challenge.

00:11:43.620 --> 00:11:46.980
Just, I guess first, in your mind then knowing.

00:11:46.980 --> 00:11:50.110
Having this information. Being able to know this information up front, right, at

00:11:50.110 --> 00:11:53.350
the beginning of your pregnancy early on. Is that something that's important to

00:11:53.350 --> 00:11:55.740
you in the process? Was that something you were happy to know about

00:11:55.740 --> 00:11:59.912
or do you wish you kind of couldn't find out maybe until later?

00:11:59.912 --> 00:12:03.010
&gt;&gt; I'm going to skirt that a little bit and I'm going to

00:12:03.010 --> 00:12:06.790
talk about it in third person because it's such a personal choice.

00:12:06.790 --> 00:12:09.040
&gt;&gt; Sure. I'm going to tell you that I

00:12:09.040 --> 00:12:12.780
have friends that fall into all of these different categories.

00:12:12.780 --> 00:12:15.222
I have one friend that buried three babies in

00:12:15.222 --> 00:12:17.862
five years because they kept coming up with that

00:12:17.862 --> 00:12:21.440
25% chance. I have one friend who has two

00:12:21.440 --> 00:12:24.400
average sized children. So they came up with that

00:12:24.400 --> 00:12:28.420
25, the other 25% twice. and I have friends

00:12:28.420 --> 00:12:32.180
that have said, oh, we'll never get pregnant. Because

00:12:32.180 --> 00:12:34.990
we don't want a dwarf child. We went through

00:12:34.990 --> 00:12:38.120
so much ourselves. We would never want that for our,

00:12:38.120 --> 00:12:41.500
a child. I have friends that say, I'm scared

00:12:41.500 --> 00:12:43.840
to death of having an average-sized child, which I

00:12:43.840 --> 00:12:46.250
don't understand because I teach high school. You know,

00:12:46.250 --> 00:12:47.810
that is not a big deal. And I have these

00:12:47.810 --> 00:12:50.000
great friends in L.A. whose son, as I just

00:12:50.000 --> 00:12:55.400
told you, is six foot four. so, you know, this,

00:12:55.400 --> 00:12:57.910
this choice that we are now given, or the

00:12:57.910 --> 00:13:03.620
access to this technology, maybe is, is very, very powerful.

00:13:03.620 --> 00:13:08.260
I'm going to tell you a quick story. We, we had a regional conference in Los

00:13:08.260 --> 00:13:14.440
Angeles about a year ago. Three women, all in their twenties, all kind

00:13:14.440 --> 00:13:18.150
of grew up together, by default, I mean not necessarily in the same town,

00:13:18.150 --> 00:13:19.850
but because they've been Little People of

00:13:19.850 --> 00:13:23.280
America members all of their lives. All pregnant.

00:13:25.540 --> 00:13:31.640
Now, they all have had the testing. One of them did not want to have

00:13:31.640 --> 00:13:34.810
the testing, for religious reasons. But, far

00:13:34.810 --> 00:13:38.590
along into the pregnancy, decided. I don't want to

00:13:38.590 --> 00:13:40.610
go through baby showers. I don't want to

00:13:40.610 --> 00:13:45.660
decorate a nursery, unless. There's a reason to.

00:13:45.660 --> 00:13:47.940
So, it's not going to change anything about

00:13:47.940 --> 00:13:50.690
the pregnancy, I'm going to go through the pregnancy,

00:13:50.690 --> 00:13:53.180
but I need to know. And so she knew

00:13:53.180 --> 00:13:56.820
she was carrying a double dominant. And there she was,

00:13:56.820 --> 00:13:59.680
with a smile on her face, with the other two

00:13:59.680 --> 00:14:03.920
women, one of whom had already buried a double dominant,

00:14:03.920 --> 00:14:06.890
and was on her second try. And knew that

00:14:06.890 --> 00:14:10.050
that one, I believe was going to be average size. And

00:14:10.050 --> 00:14:13.090
then the third young woman, knew that she was having

00:14:13.090 --> 00:14:16.780
a heterozygote dwarf and there they were all happy and

00:14:16.780 --> 00:14:23.460
talking, and I just, the strength that the girl had that knew she had

00:14:23.460 --> 00:14:28.640
a double domet inside of her, was just amazing. It gets a little bit more

00:14:28.640 --> 00:14:34.700
sad. So, the baby lived a few hours, they waited the three months that they were

00:14:34.700 --> 00:14:42.150
told to wait, They got pregnant again. And again, had the double dominant. And,

00:14:42.150 --> 00:14:45.560
and kept it. And that's their own choice, and

00:14:45.560 --> 00:14:49.993
aren't we lucky, in this country, that we have choices.

00:14:49.993 --> 00:14:54.530
&gt;&gt; Right. how much, I mean, I can't imagine, you know,

00:14:54.530 --> 00:14:58.810
the, the strength and the sort of, the, having to go through

00:14:58.810 --> 00:15:03.940
a situation like that personally. how much of the strength going through

00:15:03.940 --> 00:15:07.270
the actual reproductive process, you know, the, the joys and the pains

00:15:07.270 --> 00:15:09.270
of giving birth and, and the specifically in this

00:15:09.270 --> 00:15:12.690
case you know, being able to have access to

00:15:12.690 --> 00:15:15.400
this information and knowledge. When you do find out

00:15:15.400 --> 00:15:18.150
information if it's not the information you want, how

00:15:18.150 --> 00:15:21.100
much of that strength is derived from you personally

00:15:21.100 --> 00:15:26.100
versus a community maybe of, of other people. of,

00:15:26.100 --> 00:15:28.220
of other little people talking to the other people

00:15:28.220 --> 00:15:32.390
about this how, how is a community itself either

00:15:32.390 --> 00:15:33.930
helped or hurt in any way?

00:15:33.930 --> 00:15:39.280
&gt;&gt; Well again I can't speak from personal experience.

00:15:41.450 --> 00:15:49.350
you know I, this, this again, this technology is bittersweet. It really is. I

00:15:49.350 --> 00:15:53.820
can say that, belonging to a support

00:15:53.820 --> 00:15:55.990
group like Little People of America offers a

00:15:55.990 --> 00:16:01.870
tremendous amount of support. And we all know these statistics. We've been told

00:16:01.870 --> 00:16:06.460
these statistics since. I knew what my odds were when I was ten years old. And

00:16:06.460 --> 00:16:08.150
babysitting. And knew that I wanted to have

00:16:08.150 --> 00:16:11.040
children. And I wanted to be a teacher. I.

00:16:11.040 --> 00:16:14.350
Did that influence my selection of mate? Did

00:16:14.350 --> 00:16:16.610
I say to myself, oh I better not find,

00:16:16.610 --> 00:16:18.130
I better not fall in love with another

00:16:18.130 --> 00:16:21.920
achrondroplastic, because we have a 25% chance of having

00:16:21.920 --> 00:16:27.270
a homozygote? Absolutely not. Do I ache for my

00:16:27.270 --> 00:16:32.070
boys, who will most likely, by mere fact of,

00:16:32.070 --> 00:16:37.180
numbers will wind up with achondroplastic woman? And this will be on

00:16:37.180 --> 00:16:40.230
the table. Do I ache for them? Before they are even you know,

00:16:40.230 --> 00:16:44.190
really dating? Absolutely, I ache for them. That this is a

00:16:45.580 --> 00:16:51.038
reality in their life and so the support from the community is there.

00:16:51.038 --> 00:16:55.902
Now, again,

00:16:55.902 --> 00:16:59.210
if, the one thing I've learned over the years is just

00:16:59.210 --> 00:17:03.730
because we're all little, does not mean we have the same politics.

00:17:03.730 --> 00:17:04.069
&gt;&gt; Uh-huh.

00:17:04.069 --> 00:17:09.410
&gt;&gt; Does not mean we have the same religious convictions. And so

00:17:09.410 --> 00:17:12.760
I actually have found myself in a very awkward position. One of

00:17:12.760 --> 00:17:17.500
the reasons I'm sort of skirting away from. my position on this

00:17:17.500 --> 00:17:21.140
is that one too many times I have stated my position on this

00:17:21.140 --> 00:17:25.569
to another little person, who is just as educated about this as I am

00:17:25.569 --> 00:17:28.680
about this as I am and they have gotten up off of the conversation and

00:17:28.680 --> 00:17:33.850
walked away. And so, the support is

00:17:33.850 --> 00:17:39.120
there. But, the naysayers, or the conviction, the convicted people are

00:17:39.120 --> 00:17:44.810
also there. So it's, it's, it's a very very delicate discussion.

00:17:44.810 --> 00:17:46.330
&gt;&gt; Sure.

00:17:46.330 --> 00:17:49.130
When, when was your first introduction to this

00:17:49.130 --> 00:17:52.970
community of, of other little people? did you find

00:17:52.970 --> 00:17:54.660
that when you were still growing up as a

00:17:54.660 --> 00:17:56.680
kid? Or is this more of something you were,

00:17:56.680 --> 00:17:59.530
became, became more active in as an adult? I

00:17:59.530 --> 00:18:03.340
suspect, that my parents came home after being delivered

00:18:03.340 --> 00:18:08.480
the diagnosis by Brazelton, who probably gave them, not

00:18:08.480 --> 00:18:11.730
the website, because there were no websites. But the

00:18:11.730 --> 00:18:14.850
phone number of the local Little People of America,

00:18:14.850 --> 00:18:17.600
which I will now from here on out call LPA

00:18:17.600 --> 00:18:20.200
contact. And I suspect that by the time my

00:18:20.200 --> 00:18:22.880
parents got home, because there were no cell phones back

00:18:22.880 --> 00:18:26.150
then, they called the local contact and said, when

00:18:26.150 --> 00:18:30.443
is your next get together? So, I have known, nothing

00:18:30.443 --> 00:18:34.197
else but LPA. I was raised in LPA. And

00:18:34.197 --> 00:18:37.026
the analogy that I use with new parents I'm often

00:18:37.026 --> 00:18:39.441
put in touch with, because I, I have sort

00:18:39.441 --> 00:18:41.925
of a, little bit of a handle in, in the

00:18:41.925 --> 00:18:44.685
medical community here in the bay area, both at

00:18:44.685 --> 00:18:49.032
Stafford, at UCSF, and at the children's hospital Oakland, everybody

00:18:49.032 --> 00:18:51.863
has my phone number. So I'm often, my husband

00:18:51.863 --> 00:18:54.347
and I are often put in the position to be

00:18:54.347 --> 00:18:57.038
that phone contact, or in this day of age, the

00:18:57.038 --> 00:19:02.180
email contact. And so the advice I give those people,

00:19:02.180 --> 00:19:05.460
that originally, you know, the first Talk is typically

00:19:05.460 --> 00:19:08.340
over the phone, or on the computer. It's not face

00:19:08.340 --> 00:19:13.320
to face. Is I try to really stress the importance

00:19:13.320 --> 00:19:17.000
of joining LPA right then and there. Because it's more

00:19:17.000 --> 00:19:19.230
for the parents, at that point, than it is

00:19:19.230 --> 00:19:22.560
for the kid. And the analogy that I use, is,

00:19:22.560 --> 00:19:24.760
you know? We've all been on airplanes where the flight

00:19:24.760 --> 00:19:28.130
attendant does her, his or her spiel. And they say.

00:19:28.130 --> 00:19:31.390
Parents in event of emergency put the oxygen on yourself

00:19:31.390 --> 00:19:35.110
first and then assist your children. It's exactly the same

00:19:35.110 --> 00:19:37.340
thing in any sort of support group as far as

00:19:37.340 --> 00:19:41.090
I'm concerned. Those parents need to get to, educated, they

00:19:41.090 --> 00:19:44.170
need to get their head wrapped around this, so that

00:19:44.170 --> 00:19:47.620
when the kid does off to school at five years

00:19:47.620 --> 00:19:50.230
old, and comes home in tears, because they couldn't reach

00:19:50.230 --> 00:19:53.890
something. Because they were teased. because they couldn't reach the cafeteria

00:19:53.890 --> 00:19:58.210
line, whatever. Those parents are ready to go. They've been told in advance

00:19:58.210 --> 00:20:02.070
that those are the questions that kids are going to have. They have contacts of

00:20:02.070 --> 00:20:09.000
other parents whose kids are a couple years older. And, it just doesn't,

00:20:09.000 --> 00:20:13.420
that's just the way it should be done. And, and often times, I'll be honest,

00:20:15.490 --> 00:20:21.700
we have had very eye opening conversations with 40 somethings that were not

00:20:21.700 --> 00:20:27.180
encouraged by their families To come to LPA. And they have now found us on their

00:20:27.180 --> 00:20:34.085
own. And here they come. And often, with drink in hand at the dinnertime dance,

00:20:34.085 --> 00:20:36.530
they're, they've got their head in their

00:20:36.530 --> 00:20:40.680
hands, saying, what did I miss? Where have

00:20:40.680 --> 00:20:42.570
I been? And you know who they're mad at?

00:20:42.570 --> 00:20:43.920
&gt;&gt; Their parents.

00:20:43.920 --> 00:20:44.368
&gt;&gt; Their parents.

00:20:44.368 --> 00:20:49.930
&gt;&gt; So, Ginny, I just want to know a little bit more about you. Why don't

00:20:49.930 --> 00:20:53.720
you Just tell me where you're from and I want to know what, what you do for fun.

00:20:53.720 --> 00:20:57.380
&gt;&gt; I grew up in a suburb of Boston called Lincoln,

00:20:57.380 --> 00:21:00.970
Massachusetts. we had, we, we, were on the train line and

00:21:00.970 --> 00:21:03.180
I don't remember which line but I could. I was going

00:21:03.180 --> 00:21:05.320
into Boston on my own when I was 12 years old.

00:21:05.320 --> 00:21:05.570
&gt;&gt; Oh wow.

00:21:05.570 --> 00:21:06.020
&gt;&gt; I

00:21:06.020 --> 00:21:07.790
don't know if my parents would have allowed that in

00:21:07.790 --> 00:21:10.150
this day of age but, so lots and lots of

00:21:10.150 --> 00:21:15.010
fun. Great place to live. And then I moved to

00:21:15.010 --> 00:21:18.990
Colorado. My father was transferred just as I was starting high

00:21:18.990 --> 00:21:21.230
school. And that was a little bit unfortunate. It was

00:21:21.230 --> 00:21:25.260
two weeks before high school started, and we were uprooted. it

00:21:25.260 --> 00:21:27.510
was the best decision for my father but maybe not

00:21:27.510 --> 00:21:31.020
for me so much, because, you know. it, it's hard for

00:21:31.020 --> 00:21:35.370
a little person to break into a new situation. Especially right in the middle

00:21:35.370 --> 00:21:36.500
of hi, at the beginning of high

00:21:36.500 --> 00:21:42.170
school. but anyways, stayed in Colorado Springs. for

00:21:42.170 --> 00:21:46.620
all for years, and then got out of Dodge. Colorado Springs and my politics do

00:21:46.620 --> 00:21:52.949
not align well. So decided to come west to the bay area for college.

00:21:55.060 --> 00:21:58.340
and I've been here ever since. And, I believe that was about 25 years ago.

00:21:58.340 --> 00:21:59.850
&gt;&gt; Nice.

00:21:59.850 --> 00:22:03.910
&gt;&gt; As far as hobbies, I kind of try to get into whatever my teenage

00:22:03.910 --> 00:22:07.535
and above children are into. So that we can maybe spend some time together.

00:22:07.535 --> 00:22:07.710
[LAUGH]

00:22:07.710 --> 00:22:10.830
and I'm not And, I'm first in what it is

00:22:10.830 --> 00:22:15.375
that they're talking about. So, that's in every, ever evolving process.

00:22:15.375 --> 00:22:16.375
&gt;&gt;

00:22:15.375 --> 00:22:16.023
[LAUGH].

00:22:16.023 --> 00:22:21.440
&gt;&gt; and no matter how hard I try I, I don't seem to be up to snuff enough. But

00:22:23.030 --> 00:22:24.850
I, I by default I have to know how

00:22:24.850 --> 00:22:29.050
to sew, I do sew. economically these days it doesn't

00:22:29.050 --> 00:22:31.410
make sense to sew your clothes, it's cheaper to

00:22:31.410 --> 00:22:34.260
buy them. But by default I have to alter clothes.

00:22:34.260 --> 00:22:37.360
So I, I am in front of my sewing machine

00:22:37.360 --> 00:22:41.460
at least twice a month, altering pant, pant length and

00:22:41.460 --> 00:22:42.510
sleeve length.

00:22:42.510 --> 00:22:45.170
&gt;&gt; So, what is that...I've never thought about that before, but

00:22:45.170 --> 00:22:48.184
I mean, where, where do you shop? I mean, do you,

00:22:48.184 --> 00:22:50.070
are you, I mean, do you have to shop in different

00:22:50.070 --> 00:22:53.110
areas or places for things than most people? I'm a good old

00:22:53.110 --> 00:22:58.010
size eight, like 60% of women out there. And so I'm

00:22:58.010 --> 00:23:01.480
buying the same stuff your mom's buying. I'm bringing it home and

00:23:01.480 --> 00:23:04.375
cutting it off at the knee and probably tapering it a

00:23:04.375 --> 00:23:06.490
bit, 'because I don't want it this wide what it. You know

00:23:06.490 --> 00:23:08.670
at the knee it would be this wide so I'm tapering

00:23:08.670 --> 00:23:11.930
it. And I'm altering it, the same thing on the sleeves

00:23:11.930 --> 00:23:11.960
&gt;&gt;

00:23:11.960 --> 00:23:14.610
&gt;&gt; Because our torsos are not affected. As

00:23:14.610 --> 00:23:15.700
you can see, you and I are pretty much.

00:23:15.700 --> 00:23:16.170
&gt;&gt; Right.
&gt;&gt; Sitting

00:23:16.170 --> 00:23:16.290
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

00:23:16.290 --> 00:23:16.740
&gt;&gt; At the same height.

00:23:16.740 --> 00:23:20.590
&gt;&gt; That's really interesting. and what kinds of

00:23:20.590 --> 00:23:23.310
hobbies do your kids get you into besides,

00:23:23.310 --> 00:23:27.090
&gt;&gt; they usually involve technology or soccer, so I'm,

00:23:27.090 --> 00:23:32.990
I'm slowly learning the ropes on, social media. Soccer,

00:23:32.990 --> 00:23:35.580
I'm just really struggling with it. I sort

00:23:35.580 --> 00:23:38.280
of complain that there's a fraternity in my house

00:23:38.280 --> 00:23:43.340
and I'm the outsider. dinnertime conversations always come

00:23:43.340 --> 00:23:47.745
to soccer and I kind of disappear and nobody notices.

00:23:47.745 --> 00:23:48.745
&gt;&gt;

00:23:47.745 --> 00:23:49.600
[LAUGH]

00:23:49.600 --> 00:23:51.740
Well in sort of in line with a lot

00:23:51.740 --> 00:23:56.100
of these everyday items, I'm, I'm really curious and

00:23:56.100 --> 00:23:57.920
I'm sure other people are too. What are, are

00:23:57.920 --> 00:24:02.080
there any advantages to having a slightly shorter stature in

00:24:02.080 --> 00:24:06.200
general? this is a very common question. And I

00:24:06.200 --> 00:24:09.030
always say to myself, I gotta write it down.

00:24:09.030 --> 00:24:12.020
because I never, you know, am fully prepared. But

00:24:12.020 --> 00:24:15.090
in this instance I, I did think about it some.

00:24:15.090 --> 00:24:18.650
let's start with the disadvantages. Cause I it, that, that's a

00:24:18.650 --> 00:24:23.840
shorter list. The grocery store It's horrible. And I haven't quite

00:24:23.840 --> 00:24:26.810
figured out the best time to go. If I were not

00:24:26.810 --> 00:24:29.870
little, the best time to go, clearly, would be 6:30 or 7:00

00:24:29.870 --> 00:24:33.420
in the morning, when I'm awake because it's not crowded. But

00:24:33.420 --> 00:24:35.220
it's a very bad time for me to go when it's

00:24:35.220 --> 00:24:37.970
not crowded, because there aren't people in the aisles to turn

00:24:37.970 --> 00:24:40.990
to and say, can you hand me that jar up there. So,

00:24:40.990 --> 00:24:43.405
I think the compromise is more like 10

00:24:43.405 --> 00:24:45.870
a.m. You know, which unfortunately because I don't

00:24:45.870 --> 00:24:51.250
work full time, I can do that. And, I can always pretty much count on waiting no

00:24:51.250 --> 00:24:53.050
more than two or three minutes for somebody

00:24:53.050 --> 00:24:54.890
to show up in the aisle. I'm not going to

00:24:54.890 --> 00:24:56.700
go to customer service every time I need

00:24:56.700 --> 00:24:59.870
help. You get very savvy at flirting with people.

00:24:59.870 --> 00:25:00.870
&gt;&gt;

00:24:59.870 --> 00:25:00.354
[LAUGH]

00:25:00.354 --> 00:25:02.530
&gt;&gt; To get what you need. So I

00:25:02.530 --> 00:25:05.790
will strike up a conversation instantly, with the

00:25:05.790 --> 00:25:07.750
main motivation being that I need that can

00:25:07.750 --> 00:25:10.040
of tomatoes at the top of the counter.

00:25:10.040 --> 00:25:11.040
&gt;&gt;

00:25:10.040 --> 00:25:11.322
[LAUGH]

00:25:11.322 --> 00:25:17.360
&gt;&gt; other disadvantages, it really depends, its hard

00:25:17.360 --> 00:25:23.510
to go into communities that are less educated and less mannered. Because

00:25:23.510 --> 00:25:27.480
we are so comfortable in, in our community, which, granted,

00:25:27.480 --> 00:25:31.090
has gotten to know us. On so many different levels...

00:25:31.090 --> 00:25:31.130
&gt;&gt; Mm-hm.

00:25:31.130 --> 00:25:33.160
&gt;&gt; Over the last 20 years. My husband and

00:25:33.160 --> 00:25:37.240
I, both our careers, myself as a substitute teacher and

00:25:37.240 --> 00:25:40.180
he as a an IT guy for small

00:25:40.180 --> 00:25:45.270
businesses in our immediate area, we're very well known.

00:25:45.270 --> 00:25:45.595
&gt;&gt; Mm-hm.

00:25:45.595 --> 00:25:49.290
&gt;&gt; only because people don't forget us, you know. It's not

00:25:49.290 --> 00:25:52.380
a comment on our personality. However, I've, been told that we sort

00:25:52.380 --> 00:25:57.410
of have magnanimous personalities as well. so we get really

00:25:57.410 --> 00:26:02.570
comfortable in our environment. And then when we step out to a different

00:26:02.570 --> 00:26:08.110
environment and the reaction is totally inappropriate, it's, it's,

00:26:08.110 --> 00:26:10.810
it's a slap in the face. It's a reminder.

00:26:10.810 --> 00:26:12.270
Can you, I mean if you're comfortable, can you

00:26:12.270 --> 00:26:15.530
give us an example of a negative reaction that you.

00:26:15.530 --> 00:26:18.730
&gt;&gt; I actually can have, I can give you two. And, and, and they're a little

00:26:18.730 --> 00:26:23.000
bit different. one of them was pure ignorance.

00:26:24.180 --> 00:26:27.850
There's nothing more upsetting to me than to be

00:26:27.850 --> 00:26:31.320
in an environment where it's the adults. That are

00:26:31.320 --> 00:26:34.020
grabbing the children and saying, look at the midget, come

00:26:34.020 --> 00:26:36.900
here, come here Frankie, come look at the midget. I

00:26:36.900 --> 00:26:39.590
can not believe that in this day of age that

00:26:39.590 --> 00:26:43.710
still happening. But when I go into inner city environments,

00:26:43.710 --> 00:26:46.260
in a grocery store, you know grocery stores are really

00:26:46.260 --> 00:26:49.020
harsh places for me to be. Not only because of

00:26:49.020 --> 00:26:52.910
the physical thing but you're trapped. You know, you're in

00:26:52.910 --> 00:26:55.750
a grocery store line, and you can't go

00:26:55.750 --> 00:26:58.000
anywhere, and you've got kids with their fingers

00:26:58.000 --> 00:27:00.650
right, five feet away from you. And you're

00:27:00.650 --> 00:27:06.020
trapped. So that is definitely, you know, hard. The

00:27:06.020 --> 00:27:10.100
other example of ignorance was an educated ignorance,

00:27:10.100 --> 00:27:12.350
if I dare say. The five of us

00:27:12.350 --> 00:27:14.723
were on our bikes in San Francisco by

00:27:14.723 --> 00:27:17.950
the Palace of Fine Arts. Like we're riding our

00:27:17.950 --> 00:27:24.015
bikes around, and we rode in front of a tour bus

00:27:24.015 --> 00:27:28.950
from, with tourists from another country, that their cultural

00:27:28.950 --> 00:27:33.710
norm is to be curious, and to be scientific. And they

00:27:33.710 --> 00:27:38.250
forget appropriate behavior in that quest for

00:27:38.250 --> 00:27:43.090
curiosity! And so, we can pretty much assure that when we go by

00:27:43.090 --> 00:27:48.350
a tour bus, of, or a group of tourists from other countries. Those video cameras

00:27:48.350 --> 00:27:53.110
are trained on us like snipers. And my husband has gotten to

00:27:53.110 --> 00:27:57.690
the point. He's a very very patient man. But he will walk up right

00:27:57.690 --> 00:28:02.650
to the camera, and say you will delete that picture. He gets very upset.

00:28:02.650 --> 00:28:03.380
&gt;&gt; I imagine.

00:28:03.380 --> 00:28:08.750
&gt;&gt; And imagine having 50 of them on your family. You feel like there

00:28:08.750 --> 00:28:09.570
are snipers on you.

00:28:09.570 --> 00:28:15.080
&gt;&gt; What's the difference in your reaction to how other people

00:28:15.080 --> 00:28:20.760
respond to you? Versus how people may respond to your children. Is, are, are

00:28:20.760 --> 00:28:24.800
your feelings about this trait different for yourself versus how you see

00:28:24.800 --> 00:28:28.790
other people react to it maybe your children or other relatives or friends?

00:28:28.790 --> 00:28:30.870
&gt;&gt; I am the biggest mama bear you will

00:28:30.870 --> 00:28:33.900
ever meet. You mess with my kids watch out.

00:28:33.900 --> 00:28:39.470
&gt;&gt; Enough said. what

00:28:39.470 --> 00:28:44.100
let's go back to some of the, some of, some of the advantages.

00:28:44.100 --> 00:28:44.802
&gt;&gt; Oh yeah.

