see. Well here's a hybrid. Why don't we do the hybrid first.

00:28:52.720 --> 00:28:52.960
&gt;&gt; Okay.

00:28:52.960 --> 00:28:56.560
&gt;&gt; The spotlight is always on. Fair enough.

00:28:56.560 --> 00:29:01.070
&gt;&gt; So you can be, entertaining. And the life

00:29:01.070 --> 00:29:04.170
of the party. And everyone wants to talk to you.

00:29:04.170 --> 00:29:07.130
&gt;&gt; You could could get a, a special spot on Tales from the Genome.

00:29:07.130 --> 00:29:07.940
&gt;&gt; Yep.

00:29:10.080 --> 00:29:15.130
but let's say I've had a bad day. The spotlight's still there. I

00:29:15.130 --> 00:29:19.940
actually have a deeper appreciation for public figures. Because by default,

00:29:19.940 --> 00:29:25.150
we have become public figures. I feel I,

00:29:25.150 --> 00:29:28.230
I, can't imagine being somebody like Angelina Jolie

00:29:28.230 --> 00:29:30.850
and Brad Pitt with their children. And talk

00:29:30.850 --> 00:29:35.330
about being hunted. You know, and, and, not being able to go out for a meal.

00:29:35.330 --> 00:29:42.252
Without, the intrusion. So, that's the negative side of that spotlight.

00:29:42.252 --> 00:29:45.819
&gt;&gt; Well actually, and to go on a quick tangent, you

00:29:45.819 --> 00:29:50.691
made me realize, you know, the way little people are portrayed in

00:29:50.691 --> 00:29:55.389
the media, what aspect, I mean, what are your thoughts on

00:29:55.389 --> 00:29:59.615
that? How, how are little people portrayed in your mind? Positive, negative,

00:29:59.615 --> 00:30:03.670
in-between, mix, and how do, what is your reaction to that?

00:30:03.670 --> 00:30:09.630
&gt;&gt; Our Sidney Poitier is Peter Dinklage. I am so proud

00:30:09.630 --> 00:30:15.500
of him. And I want, along with hundreds of other little people, mostly female by

00:30:15.500 --> 00:30:20.660
the way, want to meet him. For better, for worse, he's not involved

00:30:20.660 --> 00:30:24.670
with our group, and I can't comment as to why. I would say

00:30:24.670 --> 00:30:33.150
he's quite busy these days he is the top billed actor on

00:30:33.150 --> 00:30:39.160
one of the most popular TV shows right now. He has been consistantly on the show

00:30:39.160 --> 00:30:44.530
from, I believe, day one. they're not killing him off, like they kill

00:30:44.530 --> 00:30:49.714
off everybody else. He, he will be king. I don't follow the show, but I

00:30:49.714 --> 00:30:52.512
have enough friends who are thinking, you're crazy.

00:30:52.512 --> 00:30:55.377
Why aren't you following the show? He's going to

00:30:55.377 --> 00:31:01.755
be king. And, I would like to, my husband is not into the blood and gore and

00:31:01.755 --> 00:31:08.340
sex to the degree that they are. But, I, I am keeping my eye on him. He

00:31:08.340 --> 00:31:14.440
is our Sidney Poitier. And he is up for his second Emmy in two years. Right now.

00:31:14.440 --> 00:31:14.830
&gt;&gt; So

00:31:14.830 --> 00:31:17.780
he's really been sort of a, for you. a

00:31:17.780 --> 00:31:20.760
big pivotal figure. And, and a good image of

00:31:20.760 --> 00:31:25.270
being, like. Everybody else. And he's super popular. and

00:31:25.270 --> 00:31:27.990
it's, it's, it's almost not even. I don't want to say,

00:31:27.990 --> 00:31:30.870
not noticed as a trait. But it's, it's not

00:31:30.870 --> 00:31:34.080
important in who he is, necessarily, as far as, it

00:31:34.080 --> 00:31:36.950
happens to be part of him. And so that

00:31:36.950 --> 00:31:39.830
gives visibility to the trait, but the focus on him

00:31:39.830 --> 00:31:41.210
is not because of his stature.

00:31:41.210 --> 00:31:42.145
&gt;&gt; Not in this particular

00:31:42.145 --> 00:31:42.260
[INAUDIBLE]

00:31:42.260 --> 00:31:42.590
show.

00:31:42.590 --> 00:31:43.570
&gt;&gt; Right. Exactly.

00:31:43.570 --> 00:31:46.060
&gt;&gt; he had sold himself to the devil a

00:31:46.060 --> 00:31:49.170
couple a times. He's tried real hard in the interviews

00:31:49.170 --> 00:31:51.800
that I've seen not to. I mean he has been

00:31:51.800 --> 00:31:54.220
eating out of tuna fish cans for a, you know,

00:31:54.220 --> 00:31:57.630
the beginning of his career. While offers of being

00:31:57.630 --> 00:32:00.890
leprechauns and, and, Santa's elves and so much were being

00:32:00.890 --> 00:32:04.200
thrown at him. He, he, really was keeping true to

00:32:04.200 --> 00:32:07.850
himself. There are a couple of pieces of work that

00:32:07.850 --> 00:32:09.910
I would prefer that he had not done. But

00:32:09.910 --> 00:32:13.080
for the most part, he redeemed himself with Station

00:32:13.080 --> 00:32:19.230
Agent, for which he got an Oscar and he, come to find out, he's been in a lot of

00:32:19.230 --> 00:32:22.110
little stuff, I'm going home to watch, another tv

00:32:22.110 --> 00:32:25.420
series he was in, seven episodes on, because I'm just

00:32:25.420 --> 00:32:29.310
so curious. I think it's a shame that he

00:32:29.310 --> 00:32:33.050
has not identified with our group, because he has so

00:32:33.050 --> 00:32:39.410
much to offer. up and coming pep, students

00:32:39.410 --> 00:32:43.520
that want to maybe delve into the film industry.

00:32:43.520 --> 00:32:46.200
&gt;&gt; Well, outside of Peter Dinklage, as far

00:32:46.200 --> 00:32:48.590
as media portrayal goes. Even you know, maybe

00:32:48.590 --> 00:32:50.620
not in the Hollywood sense, just in news

00:32:50.620 --> 00:32:54.530
or TV, what else have you noticed about portrayal?

00:32:54.530 --> 00:32:58.082
&gt;&gt; in the last decade, there has been a lot of curiosity

00:32:58.082 --> 00:33:01.220
with little people for a while. And I don't know if

00:33:01.220 --> 00:33:04.790
I'm allowed to say this, We were nicknaming the TLC network

00:33:04.790 --> 00:33:09.400
The Little Channel. Because they seemed heavily interested. At one point

00:33:09.400 --> 00:33:12.720
there were five or six different series going on involving little people.

00:33:12.720 --> 00:33:13.435
&gt;&gt; Mm-hm.

00:33:13.435 --> 00:33:15.990
&gt;&gt; So now that we've, seem to have lost

00:33:15.990 --> 00:33:18.060
our luster a bit. And we were one of them.

00:33:18.060 --> 00:33:20.270
But only for two episodes. Only for two. And

00:33:20.270 --> 00:33:22.800
we. We get very defensive. What we did was not

00:33:22.800 --> 00:33:29.010
reality TV. We, we, we, we prefer to call it documentary

00:33:29.010 --> 00:33:32.250
TV, is what we did for two episodes. So, I, I

00:33:32.250 --> 00:33:36.740
think the word has finally gotten out what the correct terminology

00:33:36.740 --> 00:33:39.480
is, but just in case, let me educate you on that.

00:33:41.746 --> 00:33:49.290
terminology, as you may know, evolves in different groups. So in the

00:33:49.290 --> 00:33:54.220
African American community, my mother, who was raised in the south in 30s and

00:33:54.220 --> 00:33:59.850
40s was told to call that com, that population something. That I'm not even

00:33:59.850 --> 00:34:06.810
comfortable speaking, but that's what they were called. And well they were

00:34:06.810 --> 00:34:10.179
called Negros, not the other one, Negros. And you

00:34:10.179 --> 00:34:12.920
know, I think when I came around to school

00:34:12.920 --> 00:34:15.980
in the 70s, we were told no, the word

00:34:15.980 --> 00:34:20.380
is black, and I've used the word black. And now

00:34:20.380 --> 00:34:22.790
when I use the term black, I'm told, oh

00:34:22.790 --> 00:34:25.239
no, it's African-American. But then it gets even more

00:34:25.239 --> 00:34:28.460
confusing cause I have some African-American friends that say,

00:34:28.460 --> 00:34:32.090
I wasn't born in Africa, I'm not African-American, I'm black.

00:34:32.090 --> 00:34:35.170
So, there's a lot of confusion around that, and then not to mention what the

00:34:35.170 --> 00:34:38.440
rap stars are doing with the terminology. So,

00:34:39.600 --> 00:34:42.996
the terminology. When, when Little People of America

00:34:42.996 --> 00:34:45.174
was first formed in 1957, the name

00:34:45.174 --> 00:34:49.835
was actually Midgets of America. It was primarily

00:34:49.835 --> 00:34:55.025
a venue for entertain, entertainers. and they kind

00:34:55.025 --> 00:34:57.215
of made light of the union, for lack

00:34:57.215 --> 00:35:00.940
of a better word. Well then slowly, educated,

00:35:00.940 --> 00:35:04.110
serious people started joining the group. And one

00:35:04.110 --> 00:35:08.680
of the first tasks I had, was to get rid of the word midget. Now what's

00:35:08.680 --> 00:35:13.940
wrong with the word midget, for me and many others, it conjures up the image of

00:35:15.600 --> 00:35:19.970
vaudeville, when they were called midget performers. And

00:35:19.970 --> 00:35:23.210
they would go around, much like a travelling circus.

00:35:23.210 --> 00:35:27.530
And they would get on stage. And you would see, a little person

00:35:27.530 --> 00:35:32.550
like myself, with a cigar hanging out of their mouth, and a diaper on.

00:35:32.550 --> 00:35:33.820
&gt;&gt; Mm hm.

00:35:33.820 --> 00:35:37.360
&gt;&gt; And making total fools of themselves. So when

00:35:37.360 --> 00:35:39.570
I hear the word midget, that's what I conjure

00:35:39.570 --> 00:35:43.190
up in my mind, as do, many in our

00:35:43.190 --> 00:35:46.360
organizations. So I think the word is finally dying.

00:35:46.360 --> 00:35:47.370
&gt;&gt; Mm-hm.

00:35:47.370 --> 00:35:48.630
&gt;&gt; occasionally

00:35:48.630 --> 00:35:52.200
it will be used, In hockey leagues, it's

00:35:52.200 --> 00:35:55.190
still used up in Canada, a, a, signifying the

00:35:55.190 --> 00:35:58.490
younger kids I think, and and I, I think

00:35:58.490 --> 00:36:01.630
the little people group up there has been really

00:36:01.630 --> 00:36:05.130
working on that. so the terminology that I'm

00:36:05.130 --> 00:36:08.410
comfortable with, long-winded answer, is I'm comfortable with little

00:36:08.410 --> 00:36:10.950
person and I'm comfortable with dwarf, because that's what

00:36:10.950 --> 00:36:13.810
I was raised with. Now, that's not to say

00:36:13.810 --> 00:36:16.770
that my children, and they're okay with that too, but

00:36:16.770 --> 00:36:19.440
maybe my grandchildren will have come up with a new term.

00:36:21.010 --> 00:36:23.480
&gt;&gt; Right. Actually, and, and I probably won't

00:36:23.480 --> 00:36:25.050
include what I'm about to say, but you made

00:36:25.050 --> 00:36:26.520
me think of it, and it's just so amazing

00:36:26.520 --> 00:36:28.510
to make the connection that, y'know, I think in

00:36:28.510 --> 00:36:31.200
the, as far as sexuality is concerned in the

00:36:31.200 --> 00:36:33.620
gay community. I mean the evolution of those, of

00:36:33.620 --> 00:36:35.680
the nomenclature of the name, and what people are

00:36:35.680 --> 00:36:38.970
comfortable with and, in one way I'm fascinated with,

00:36:38.970 --> 00:36:42.760
because it's a group identifier. And I honestly think people should,

00:36:42.760 --> 00:36:46.650
y'know, we should respect groups enough to call them what they want

00:36:46.650 --> 00:36:48.880
ot be called. You know, and I think in the gay community,

00:36:48.880 --> 00:36:51.320
you know, there are people who live and die by the word

00:36:51.320 --> 00:36:54.780
queer. you know, that's what they want to be called. They reclaimed

00:36:54.780 --> 00:36:57.070
it. There are other people who identify as gay. There are other

00:36:57.070 --> 00:36:59.970
people who identify, you know, you know I, I, in several different

00:36:59.970 --> 00:37:03.550
ways. And the community argues about it all the time. You know,

00:37:04.700 --> 00:37:07.030
internally you know, like, no we shouldn't use

00:37:07.030 --> 00:37:09.170
this word, or we shouldn't use that word. And

00:37:09.170 --> 00:37:11.000
then that can even be confusing for people in

00:37:11.000 --> 00:37:12.825
the outside looking in cause then they're like well.

00:37:12.825 --> 00:37:13.820
&gt;&gt; What do we do?

00:37:13.820 --> 00:37:19.010
&gt;&gt; What do we do? so it, it's amazing to parallels there between.

00:37:19.010 --> 00:37:20.420
&gt;&gt; That's that book that I want you to read.

00:37:20.420 --> 00:37:21.620
&gt;&gt; Yeah, I'm definitely going to check that out.

00:37:21.620 --> 00:37:26.450
&gt;&gt; So I have an adorable story to tell of my 15 year old who.

00:37:28.760 --> 00:37:30.620
I need to remind myself is indeed a

00:37:30.620 --> 00:37:35.270
really great kid because sometimes I, I forget that.

00:37:35.270 --> 00:37:37.810
He was a, a coach this summer for

00:37:37.810 --> 00:37:41.830
summer sports camp, he's very, very athletically minded and

00:37:41.830 --> 00:37:44.980
unfortunately, do to being only four feet tall.

00:37:44.980 --> 00:37:48.350
is not athletically bodied. Now, put him amongst other

00:37:48.350 --> 00:37:50.330
little people and he's going to bring home the gold

00:37:50.330 --> 00:37:54.900
medals. But, when the population is one in 20000,

00:37:54.900 --> 00:37:58.640
that's just not going to happen on a daily, weekly, it happens on an

00:37:58.640 --> 00:38:03.480
annual basis. So next week, we're going to the world games for little

00:38:03.480 --> 00:38:07.450
people, and I suspect that my 15 year old will be setting records

00:38:07.450 --> 00:38:09.750
in all of the different events that he is going to be doing.

00:38:09.750 --> 00:38:12.060
&gt;&gt; So exciting.

00:38:12.060 --> 00:38:15.220
&gt;&gt; So he, with my urging, took this job over the

00:38:15.220 --> 00:38:20.588
summer where he was a coach in training with a third party

00:38:20.588 --> 00:38:24.880
sports camp. And every day, I would say, okay,

00:38:24.880 --> 00:38:26.920
you gotta give me one story, you know, based on

00:38:26.920 --> 00:38:29.040
the day, tell me one little thing that happened.

00:38:30.050 --> 00:38:31.920
And one of these days, he came home, he says,

00:38:31.920 --> 00:38:36.290
well, something interesting happened today. So I stopped everything

00:38:36.290 --> 00:38:38.470
I was doing, so I could listen. But you can't

00:38:38.470 --> 00:38:40.360
ask too many questions, because then he closes up

00:38:40.360 --> 00:38:45.830
again. He says, somebody asked what time it was, and

00:38:45.830 --> 00:38:50.340
I pulled out my cell phone. And the kid said, what?

00:38:50.340 --> 00:38:54.510
You have a cell phone? That's not fair. You're only eight.

00:38:55.560 --> 00:39:00.370
And Ben said, no I'm about to be 16, and the kid

00:39:00.370 --> 00:39:05.695
said, oh, that's right you're a midget. And Ben said,

00:39:05.695 --> 00:39:08.800
[SOUND]

00:39:08.800 --> 00:39:13.250
well actually Sammy, I'm, I'm not a midget. Midgets a

00:39:13.250 --> 00:39:18.790
really mean word, I would rather you call me a dwarf.

00:39:18.790 --> 00:39:22.180
Or a little person but you know what, Sammy? You met

00:39:22.180 --> 00:39:24.340
me two days ago so you should be calling me Ben.

00:39:24.340 --> 00:39:27.590
&gt;&gt; What a great answer.

00:39:27.590 --> 00:39:30.470
&gt;&gt; And I said, Ben, was there an audience for that

00:39:30.470 --> 00:39:34.080
discussion? He said nope, there was just me and Sammy. And

00:39:34.080 --> 00:39:39.700
I said, Ben, some'ing tells me, that when they all went home,

00:39:39.700 --> 00:39:44.140
Sammy got into the car and told his mother about the whole conversation. And Ben

00:39:44.140 --> 00:39:49.390
said oh, mother, pfft. The next day, Sammy brought

00:39:49.390 --> 00:39:54.640
Ben a card that was handwritten in cursive about how

00:39:54.640 --> 00:39:59.626
great it was to have Ben as his coach, and that he would never use the M-word

00:39:59.626 --> 00:40:00.354
ever again.

00:40:01.500 --> 00:40:04.510
&gt;&gt; What is, what is driving a car like? I mean do you,

00:40:04.510 --> 00:40:06.640
I mean, do you have any, like, do you have to have something?

00:40:06.640 --> 00:40:07.800
&gt;&gt; What is driving your car like?

00:40:07.800 --> 00:40:10.270
&gt;&gt; Well I know, but I'm asking like, foot pedals though. Like, is that?

00:40:10.270 --> 00:40:10.650
&gt;&gt; I do.

00:40:10.650 --> 00:40:10.950
&gt;&gt; Okay.

00:40:10.950 --> 00:40:13.940
&gt;&gt; I have we have extension pedals.

00:40:13.940 --> 00:40:14.580
&gt;&gt; Oh okay.

00:40:14.580 --> 00:40:15.872
&gt;&gt; That bolt on to the

00:40:15.872 --> 00:40:16.560
[INAUDIBLE]

00:40:16.560 --> 00:40:20.080
that you use. There are steel bars With,

00:40:20.080 --> 00:40:22.250
you know, C clamps and all that hardware

00:40:22.250 --> 00:40:24.190
that I don't know what it's called. Takes

00:40:24.190 --> 00:40:26.820
about 45 minutes to put them on. Not much

00:40:26.820 --> 00:40:31.680
fun. takes about 10 minutes to take them off. So I could drive your car if I

00:40:31.680 --> 00:40:34.270
brought my extra set of extension pedals and

00:40:34.270 --> 00:40:36.860
I was totally limber and could fold myself up

00:40:36.860 --> 00:40:37.210
[LAUGH]

00:40:37.210 --> 00:40:40.080
into a small little ball and be upside-down with

00:40:40.080 --> 00:40:44.090
my, hex wrenches and all that sort of stuff. And

00:40:44.090 --> 00:40:46.100
if you wanted to drive my car, no problem, you

00:40:46.100 --> 00:40:47.500
would just have to take them off, and I would

00:40:47.500 --> 00:40:49.250
ask you very nicely to put them back on

00:40:49.250 --> 00:40:54.490
when you were done. So, when I was going down

00:40:54.490 --> 00:40:58.420
to Los Angeles to interview during college, with the you

00:40:58.420 --> 00:41:02.670
know, the film industry, I rented a car in Burbank,

00:41:02.670 --> 00:41:08.100
and I put them on myself in my business suit. And proceeded to get on the

00:41:08.100 --> 00:41:13.450
five in Burbank, and about 300 yards between,

00:41:13.450 --> 00:41:16.040
ahead of the intersection of the five and

00:41:16.040 --> 00:41:23.230
the ten, my gas pedal falls off. And I have nowhere to go. Except for the

00:41:23.230 --> 00:41:25.590
shoulder that really wasn't a shoulder. And I

00:41:25.590 --> 00:41:27.920
had to drift, because there was no gas.

00:41:29.190 --> 00:41:33.310
So there was not enough room on the shoulder to open the driver's door for

00:41:33.310 --> 00:41:39.050
somebody to come help me. So, Eventually, a

00:41:39.050 --> 00:41:44.280
Latino guy pulls over, and between

00:41:44.280 --> 00:41:49.880
his limited English. My limited Spanish. He offered to help. But he had to get

00:41:49.880 --> 00:41:54.310
into this rental car and drive it with me in it. And drive it off

00:41:54.310 --> 00:42:01.150
of this freeway. In order to do it. So I was saying a few prayers at that

00:42:01.150 --> 00:42:04.210
point, and everything was fine. He fixed it and

00:42:04.210 --> 00:42:06.880
he followed me, he asked if he could follow

00:42:06.880 --> 00:42:11.430
me to where I was going to make sure I got there. That was the last time I

00:42:11.430 --> 00:42:14.938
ever put extension pedals on a rental car. Soon

00:42:14.938 --> 00:42:19.340
after that, the, I don't know if it was

00:42:19.340 --> 00:42:22.380
Reagan or Bush, But one of them did something

00:42:22.380 --> 00:42:27.020
very nice, called the Americans with Disabilities Act. And

00:42:27.020 --> 00:42:30.490
that means, now, that, as long as I give

00:42:30.490 --> 00:42:34.280
my rental car company 24 hours notice, they have

00:42:34.280 --> 00:42:38.820
to have a car waiting for me with hand controls. So I just did it today as a

00:42:38.820 --> 00:42:41.890
matter of fact for my trip next week, and

00:42:41.890 --> 00:42:44.430
doesn't cost me any extra. I get to walk

00:42:44.430 --> 00:42:46.660
right off that airplane into my rental car just

00:42:46.660 --> 00:42:49.720
like you do. I had to get comfortable with driving

00:42:49.720 --> 00:42:53.910
with hand controls, and it's hard. legal or not,

00:42:53.910 --> 00:42:57.060
I used to, still maybe do use my cell phone

00:42:57.060 --> 00:42:59.490
a little bit when I'm driving. And you can't

00:42:59.490 --> 00:43:02.980
do that with hand controls because one hand is always

00:43:02.980 --> 00:43:05.070
on the steering wheel. And the other hand is

00:43:05.070 --> 00:43:08.199
on the mechanism that acts as your gas and brake.

